China silences last voice of dissent on Xinjiang - Telegraph
The only public figure inside China who dared to question Beijing's policy in the vast, oil-rich and troubled region of Xinjiang is now facing life imprisonment.
Ilham Tohti, a 44-year-old economics professor at China's Ethnic Minorities university in Beijing, has been charged with "separatism" along with seven of his students, according to his lawyer.
"They were all arrested in Beijing. Tohti faces ten years to life in prison for being the ringleader. His students face three to 10 years," said Li Fangping.
"He is being detained in Xinjiang and currently the authorities will not allow any lawyers to represent him or see him. I am trying to be involved. His family in Beijing are not formally under house arrest, but they cannot leave their house freely or meet anyone."
Mr Tohti has suffered constant harassment from the authorities since founding a website, Uighurbiz, in 2005 that became the main forum for debate over China's often repressive policies in Xinjiang.

